{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181003072231|862264747","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Adriano_Espaillat","to":"Adriano Espaillat"}],"pages":{"2118902":{"pageid":2118902,"ns":0,"title":"Adriano Espaillat","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-11T11:56:13Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Spanish name|Espaillat|Cabral}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Adriano Espaillat\n| image = Adriano Espaillat 115th Congress photo.jpg\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| district = {{ushr|NY|13|13th}}\n| term_start = January 3, 2017\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Charles Rangel]]\n| successor =\n| state_senate1 = New York\n| district1 = 31st\n| term_start1 = January 1, 2011\n| term_end1 = December 31, 2016\n| predecessor1 = [[Eric Schneiderman]]\n| successor1 = [[Marisol Alcantara]]\n| state_assembly2 = New York\n| district2 = 72nd\n| term_start2 = January 1, 1997\n| term_end2 = December 31, 2010\n| predecessor2 = John Murtaugh\n| successor2 = [[Guillermo Linares]]\n| birth_name = {{nowrap|Adriano de Jes\u00fas Espaillat Cabral}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|9|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Santiago de los Caballeros|Santiago]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse =\n| children = 2\n| education = [[Queens College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| website = {{url|espaillat.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Adriano de Jes\u00fas Espaillat Cabral''' {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0251\u02d0|d|r|i|\u02c8|\u0251\u02d0|n|o\u028a|_|\u02cc|\u025b|s|p|a\u026a|\u02c8|j|\u0251\u02d0|t}} (born September 27, 1954) is a [[Dominican-American]] politician. He is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|NY|13}} and the first formerly [[undocumented immigrant]] to ever serve in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/adriano-espaillat-undocumented_us_5822a7e2e4b0d9ce6fbfdfc1|title=Adriano Espaillat Becomes First Formerly Undocumented Immigrant In Congress|last=Moreno|first=Carolina|date=2016-11-09|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2017-02-25}}</ref> Previously, he served as a member of the [[New York State Senate]] and as a member of the [[New York State Assembly]].<ref name=\"dominicana\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lanaciondominicana.com/ver_noticia.php?id_noticia=15359&sesion_periodico=41 |title=El poder politico de Nueva York tambien honr\u00f3 el dia de Duarte |language=Spanish |publisher=La Naci\u00f3n Dominicana |date=February 1, 2010 |accessdate=February 6, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111171611/http://lanaciondominicana.com/ver_noticia.php?id_noticia=15359&sesion_periodico=41 |archive-date=2014-11-11 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>\n\nEspaillat was a ranking member of the New York Senate Housing, Construction and Community Development Committee and Chair of the Senate Latino Caucus. Espaillat represented the neighborhoods of Marble Hill, Inwood, Fort George, Washington Heights, Hamilton Heights, West Harlem, and the Upper West Side in Manhattan.\n\nEspaillat is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]. On November 8, 2016, Espaillat was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[New York's 13th congressional district]] to succeed retiring [[Charles Rangel]]. He is the first Dominican-American member of Congress.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cdn.com.do/noticias/estados-unidos/2017/01/03/adriano-espaillat-es-juramentado-como-congresista-de-eeuu/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-01-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104163056/http://www.cdn.com.do/noticias/estados-unidos/2017/01/03/adriano-espaillat-es-juramentado-como-congresista-de-eeuu/ |archive-date=2017-01-04 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nEspaillat was born on September 27, 1954 in [[Santiago de los Caballeros|Santiago]], [[Dominican Republic]]<ref name=\"Official bio\"/><ref name=\"New Members 2011\"/> to Melba (n\u00e9e Rodr\u00edguez) and Ulises Espaillat. Espaillat is a great-grandson of Dominican President [[Ulises Espaillat]].<ref>{{cite news|title=De Washington Heitghts a Washington DC, Espaillat rompe 70 a\u00f1os de poder afroamericano|url=http://www.elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=485900|accessdate=9 November 2016|publisher=El Nuevo Diario|date=1 July 2016|location=New York|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Eligon|first1=John|title=Running for the House on Pride in His Roots, and Pure Energy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/19/nyregion/state-senator-adriano-espaillat-runs-for-the-house-on-pride-and-energy.html|accessdate=9 November 2016|publisher=The New York Times|date=18 June 2012|quote=Mr. Espaillat says he is a descendant of one of the Dominican Republic's most notable political figures \u2014 Ulises Francisco Espaillat, who held the presidency for about five months in 1876.}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Bishop Dubois High School]] in 1974 and earned his [[bachelor of science|B.S.]] degree in political science at [[Queens College]] in 1978.<ref name=\"Official bio\"/>\n\n==Earlier career==\nEspaillat served as the Manhattan Court Services Coordinator for the New York City Criminal Justice Agency, a non-profit organization that provides indigent legal services and works to reduce unnecessary pretrial detention and post-sentence incarceration costs. As a state-certified conflict resolution mediator and volunteer with the Washington Heights Inwood Conflict Resolutions and Mediation Center, Espaillat helped resolve hundreds of conflicts.<ref name=\"nysenate.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nysenate.gov/senator/adriano-espaillat/bio|title=Senator Adriano Espaillat|publisher=|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe later worked as Director of the Washington Heights Victims Services Community Office, an organization offering counseling and other services to families of victims of homicides and other crimes. From 1994 to 1996, Espaillat served as the Director of Project Right Start, a national initiative funded by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation to combat substance abuse by educating the parents of pre-school children.<ref name=\"nysenate.gov\"/>\n\nPrior to his election to the New York State Assembly, Espaillat was an active voice on New York City Community Board 12, and President of the 34th Precinct Community Council. Espaillat also served on Governor Mario Cuomo's Dominican-American Advisory Board from 1991-1993.<ref name=\"nysenate.gov\"/>\n\n==New York State Assembly==\n\nEspaillat served in the New York State Assembly from 1997 to 2010. He was first elected after defeating 16-year incumbent John Brian Murtaugh in the 1996 Democratic Primary. Espaillat chaired the Black, Puerto Rican, Hispanic & Asian Legislative Caucus, and committees on small business and children & families.\n\nIn the Assembly, Espaillat was a vocal advocate for tenants, consumers, veterans, immigrants and local businesses. He passed laws encouraging the construction and preservation of affordable housing, giving low-income day care workers the right to organize and obtain health care, and sponsored measures to improve hospital translation services. He also established a higher education scholarship fund for relatives of the victims of American Airlines Flight 587, which crashed on November 12, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Assembly Task Force on New Americans|url=http://assembly.state.ny.us/comm/NewAmer/20030225/|work=2002 Report}}</ref> Despite national Republican and conservative criticism, Espaillat strongly supported efforts in 2007 to allow undocumented immigrants to obtain driver's licenses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hakim|first=Danny|title=Spitzer Tries New Tack on Immigrant Licenses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/nyregion/28spitzer.html?pagewanted=all|newspaper=New York Times|date=October 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter a wave of assaults and murders against livery cab drivers in 2000 that left over 10 dead, Espaillat passed legislation strengthening penalties for violent crimes against livery drivers and enabled their families to receive New York State Crime Victims Board funding. Livery cabs work in less affluent neighborhoods of New York that typically lack access to yellow cabs.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fountain|first=John|title=Stricter Sentences for Livery-Cab Crimes|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 13, 2000}}</ref>\n\nEspaillat took legal action against power utility Con Edison after equipment failures led to a two-day blackout in Upper Manhattan, in July 1999, that caused financial damage to restaurants, bodegas and other small businesses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wald|first=Matthew|title=Nuclear Agency Delays Reopening of Con Ed's Indian Point 2 Plant|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 21, 2000}}</ref> Con Edison subsequently agreed to invest an additional $100 million in Upper Manhattan electrical infrastructure at no cost to ratepayers and was required to refund customers billed for expenses related to the blackout.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perez-Pena|first=Richard|title=Pataki Signs Bill Requiring Con Ed Rebate|newspaper=New York Times|date=August 9, 2000}}</ref>\n\n==New York State Senate==\n\n[[File:Brewer Espaillat 563 Columbus Av 87 St jeh.jpg|thumb|left|Office on Columbus Avenue]]\n\n=== Elections ===\n\n==== 2010 ====\nEspaillat ran for Senate in 2010 after incumbent Democrat [[Eric Schneiderman]] announced his campaign for [[New York Attorney General]]. Espaillat received more than 50% of the vote in a four-way Democratic party. In 2012, Espaillat defeated then-Assemblyman Guillermo Linares 62% - 38% in the Democratic Primary.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2012/09/14/espaillat-defeats-linares-state-senate-primary-race|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20121221045026/http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2012/09/14/espaillat-defeats-linares-state-senate-primary-race|dead-url=yes|archive-date=December 21, 2012|title=Espaillat defeats Linares in State Senate primary|date=September 14, 2012|newspaper=Columbia Spectator|df=}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014 ====\nFollowing his loss to Rangel in the Democratic primary, Espaillat announced his re-election bid for his State Senate seat, facing former City Councilman Robert Jackson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2014/06/26/after-loss-to-rangel-espaillat-to-focus-on-re-election-in-albany/|title=After loss to Rangel, Espaillat to focus on re-election in Albany|last1=Toback|first1=Ross|date=June 26, 2014|work=New York Post|last2=Campanile|first2=Carl}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, Espaillat won his bid for re-election to the Senate by a very narrow margin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://columbiaspectator.com/news/2014/09/10/espaillat-re-elected-state-senate-slight-majority-over-jackson|title=Espaillat re-elected to State Senate in slight majority over Jackson - Columbia Daily Spectator|publisher=|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\nIn 2011, Espaillat led the fight to safeguard and strengthen rent regulation for over 1 million affordable housing apartments that was set to expire that year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/uptown/freshman-state-sen-espaillat-bat-1m-tenants-rent-regulation-article-1.109933|title=Freshman state Sen. Espaillat going to bat for more than 1M tenants from rent regulation changes|last=Lombardi|first=Frank|date=April 14, 2011|newspaper=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref> While tenant protections had been weakened in the past, the agreement reached that year made it more difficult to convert affordable housing to market rate and created a new Tenant Protection Unit within the state's housing agency.\n\nEspaillat also passed legislation increasing enforcement against businesses that sell alcohol to minors and authored the Notary Public Advertising Act, to crack down on unscrupulous public notaries who prey on vulnerable immigrants by offering fraudulent legal services.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bronxpresspolitics.blogspot.com/2011/07/smiling-dynamo-recounts-rookie-year.html|title=Smiling Dynamo recounts rookie year|last=McHugh|first=Brendan|date=July 6, 2011|newspaper=Bronx Press Politics}}</ref> He voted in favor of marriage equality legislation in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20110608/washington-heights-inwood/latino-politicians-call-on-albany-pass-marriage-equality-legislation|title=Latino Politicians Call on Albany to Pass Marriage Equality Legislation|last=Zanoni|first=Carla|date=June 8, 2011|newspaper=DNAinfo|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118120444/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20110608/washington-heights-inwood/latino-politicians-call-on-albany-pass-marriage-equality-legislation|archivedate=November 18, 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\n===NYS Senate committee assignments===\n* Housing, Construction & Community Development (Ranking Member)\n* Environmental Conservation\n* Higher Education\n* Codes\n* Rules\n* Judiciary\n* Finance\n* Insurance\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n=== Elections ===\n\n====2012====\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2012#District 13}}\nIn 2012, Espaillat ran in the Democratic primary for New York's 13th Congressional District, in a crowded field that included 42-year incumbent Charles Rangel. The seat had long been a majority-black district, but demographic change made it a 55 percent Hispanic district.<ref name=\"wapo-vuln\">{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/post/charles-rangel-more-vulnerable-than-ever/2012/05/11/gIQA5Gt9HU_blog.html | title=Charles Rangel more vulnerable than ever  | author=Weiner, Rachel | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | date=May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRangel narrowly beat Espaillat 44% to 42%, with a margin of victory of less than 1,000 votes. Espaillat placed first in the Bronx section of the district and parts of Upper Manhattan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/results/2012/FederalPrimary/1.14%20CROSSOVER%20DEM%20CONGRESS%20DISTRICT%2013%20RECAP.pdf|title=Board of Elections Results}}</ref>\n\nThe election was marked by reports that Spanish-speaking voters were either turned away at the polls or forced to use affidavit ballots.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/10/nyregion/adriano-espaillat-concedes-defeat-by-charles-rangel-will-drop-challenge.html|title=Rangel's Opponent Gives Up And Will Halt Court Challenge|last=Chen|first=David|date=July 9, 2012|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> The New York City Board of Elections was also sharply criticized for its poor handling of the election and subsequent legal proceedings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/troubling-actions-board-elex-members-article-1.1108812|title=Troubling actions by Board of Elex members|last=Gonzalez|first=Juan|date=July 6, 2012|newspaper=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2014#District 13}}\nIn 2014, Espaillat ran against incumbent Charlie Rangel again, losing for the second consecutive time, 47.7% to 43.1%.\n\n====2016====\nIn November 2015, Espaillat announced he would give up his State Senate seat to run for Congress again. He was running in an open seat; Rangel had announced in 2014 that he would not seek a 22nd term in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/candidates-replace-rep-charles-rangel-article-1.2423776|title=Field of candidates looking to replace Rep. Charles Rangel increases by two|last=Blain|first=Glenn|date=November 4, 2015|work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref> In the Democratic primary\u2014the real contest in this heavily Democratic district\u2014he narrowly defeated his nearest challenger, state assemblyman [[Keith L. T. Wright]], with 36 percent of the vote. As expected, he won the general election handily, taking over 81 percent of the vote to become only the third person to represent what is now the 13th in 72 years. [[Adam Clayton Powell, Jr.]] held the district from 1945 to 1971; Rangel had won the seat after defeating Powell in the 1970 primary. The district had been numbered as the 22nd District from 1945 to 1953, the 16th from 1953 to 1963, the 18th from 1963 to 1973, the 19th from 1973 to 1983, the 16th from 1983 to 1993, the 15th from 1993 to 2013, and has been the 13th since 2013.\n\n=== Tenure ===\nEspaillat serves as a member of the Foreign Affairs Committee, the Committee on Education and the Workforce, and the Select Committee on Small Business. He is a member of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus (CHC) and was appointed as Chairman of the CHC Task Force for Transportation, Infrastructure and Housing.\n\nIn August 2017, following the aftermath of the [[2017 Unite the Right rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], Espaillat and Pennsylvania Representative [[Dwight E. Evans]] introduced legislation banning [[Confederate monuments]] on federal property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/347026-democrats-unveil-bill-to-ban-confederate-monuments-on-federal-property|title=Dems unveil bill to ban Confederate monuments on federal property|first=Cristina|last=Marcos|date=17 August 2017|publisher=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n* [[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|'''Committee on Education and the Workforce''']]\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|'''Committee on Foreign Affairs''']]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Small Business|'''Committee on Small Business''']]\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Health and Technology|Subcommittee on Health and Technology]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]] (Chairman of the CHC Task Force for Transportation, Infrastructure and Housing)<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalhispaniccaucus-lujangrisham.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Hispanic Caucus|date=|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus]]\n* [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Caucus Members|author=|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|format=|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|date=|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Hispanic Americans in the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Official bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nysenate.gov/senator/adriano-espaillat/bio|title=Adriano Espaillat: Biography|publisher=[[New York State Senate]]|accessdate=March 13, 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"New Members 2011\">{{cite web|url=http://nycapitolnews.com/features/2011-01-06/2052.html |title=Legislative Preview: Meet The New Members |work=The Capitol |publisher=[[Manhattan Media]] |date=January 6, 2011 |accessdate=March 13, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://espaillat.house.gov Congressman Adriano Espaillat] official